When we query mongos 3.2 or 3.4 with a read preference and read concern, the command should be assembled like:
{noformat}
{
  "$query": {
    "find": "test", "filter": {}, "readConcern": {"level": "majority"}
  },
  "$readPreference": {
    "mode": "secondary"
  }
}
{noformat}
However, the driver sends:
{noformat}
{
  "$query": {
    "find": "test", "filter": {}, "readConcern": {"level": "majority"}
  },
  "$readPreference": {
    "mode": "secondary"
  },
  "readConcern": {"level": "majority"}
}
{noformat}
mongos apparently ignores the outer readConcern.

The {{ASSERT_CMP}} macros like {{ASSERT_CMPINT}} use the arguments that are being compared directly in the error message.

For example, the {{ASSERT_CMPINT}} approximately looks like:

{code}
#define ASSERT_CMPINT(a, b)                  \
if (a != b) {                                \
   printf("assert failure: %d != %d", a, b); \
   abort();                                  \ 
} 
{code}

The caveat is that if {{a}} or {{b}} are function calls (that aren't idempotent), the error message might be misleading.

[Here's an example|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-c-driver/blob/master/src/libbson/tests/test-json.c#L849-L850] of one such case:
{code}
ASSERT_CMPINT (
    0, ==, bson_json_reader_read (reader, &bson_out, &error));
{code}

Since {{b}} is substituted for that function call, that function gets called twice, and the error message could produce something confusing like "0 != 0".

Quoting the [CRUD spec|https://github.com/mongodb/specifications/blob/master/source/crud/crud.rst] on {{arrayFilters}}:

{quote}
This option is sent only if the caller explicitly provides a value. The default is to not send a value. For servers < 3.6, the driver MUST raise an error if the caller explicitly provides a value. For unacknowledged writes using opcodes, the driver MUST raise an error if the caller explicitly provides a value.
{quote}

It doesn't appear that libmongoc checks the wire version when {{arrayFilters}} is used. This may need treatment similar to what is done for {{collation}}, which is tracked when used for any individual write or one or more operations within command executed as part of a bulk write.
